An American, two classes of citizens
New York - At the time I wrote this article, officials across the United States were still counting ballots from the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the final tally is confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
In this fiercely contested and record-breaking election, this was to be expected.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the election of the U.S. president, but this choice affects people all over the place.
If it's still too early to determine the election results, then it's not too early to discuss the implications of this election on the world's most powerful nation.
From a positive perspective, the United States is still a powerful democratic country.
Despite being constrained by actual limitations related to the pandemic, voter participation remains high.
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
And violent events are rare.
The court is investigating the decision of the US Postal Service, which seems to be made for political motives, to hinder the delivery of votes from areas where votes are expected to mainly come from the Democratic Party.
US President Trump made an unfounded victory declaration on Tuesday evening, which received almost no response, and his demand to stop the counting (at least in the states where he is leading) seems to be ignored.
However, it is worrisome that the divisions among American voters are still very large.
The votes for the two candidates are almost equal.
Not surprisingly, this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The governor and state legislative seats are almost evenly divided between the two parties (with a slight Republican advantage).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, possibly winning around 40-50 million votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip in the Senate, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not come from hardline authorization, nor from political adjustments.
Trump's poll numbers are very good, and he gained 5 million more votes than in 2016, the second-highest number of votes ever received by a presidential candidate in US history, and more than any previous winner.
Notably, this happened in the context of a new high in daily COVID-19 cases (100,000+), and deaths (over 1,000).
At a time when the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic are becoming most severe, nearly half of voters have turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, he will still have significant rhetorical power, especially if he remains in the public eye (which also seems possible).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant impact on the Republican Party's nominee selection in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Not surprisingly, despite having no evidence, Trump has been striving to appear virtuous and honest, and has been attempting to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accuse fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden as president.
Trump may never admit defeat, let alone attend the inauguration of the next president.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never met a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They divide themselves into separate communities and regions based on their similar views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable news channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
While the lack of civic education has provided an advantage for the division of different age groups.
It is worth noting that the division of the country is not usually divided along economic lines.
People from different social classes have voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race are not as one-sided as many people predicted.
Their differences are mainly over the relief measures.
Education level is obviously an indicator of political orientation, and geographical location is also the same. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in big city areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be more significant than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in elections, except for mobilizing specific constituencies, such as large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in southern Florida.
In this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms in the way presidential elections are held or the way governments operate.
This situation is similar to the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws, lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solutions will benefit some people at the expense of others.
It is not surprising that those who will be harmed by the change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This depends to a large extent on the judgment of Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell and his ability and willingness to cooperate with future President Biden.
Cooperation also requires Biden to make concessions, which will certainly be resisted by his party members who are stronger in ideology.
Democrats have tried to sharply deny everything associated with Trump and his representatives.
But they failed.
What the Republicans sought was an election that would recognize Trump.
But that also did not happen as they had wished.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
